itizens. To understand citizenship from the perspective of noncitizens, this book utilizes interviews with more than one-hundred immigrants of varying legal statuses about their attempts to integrate economically, socially, politically, and legally during a modern era of intense immigration enforcement. Studying the experiences of green card holders, refugees, military service members, temporary workers, international students, and undocumented immigrants uncovers the common plight that underlies their distinctions: limited legal status breeds a sense of citizenship insecurity for all immigrants that inhibits their full integration into society. Bringing together theories of citizenship with empirical data on integration and analysis of contemporary policy, Chen builds a case that formal citizenship status matters more than ever during times of enforcement and argues for constructing pathways to citizenship that enhance both formal and substantive equality of immigrants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited States. 0aNaturalizationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aImmigrants.  acitizenship.  acontemporary.  aequality.  aintegration.  apathways.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishz978311070486008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020z9783110704587oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361276140uhttps: